The paper deals with geometric set systems and their packing numbers, which are fundamental concepts in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms and the use of combinatorial techniques, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Additionally, the paper discusses the application of its results to geometric discrepancy and optimization problems, which could place it under cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis).
